english:
  title: Where Can One Forget the Wine?
  author: Yu Ho-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Where can one forget the wine?
    Twenty years guarding the frontier,
    the border moon hangs low at dusk,
    the blue sea touches the barbarian sky.
    Iron cavalry keeps eternal watch,
    yet letters from home never arrive on crane's wing.
    Without a cup to drink in such hours,
    the exile's heart grows only more desolate.

    Where can one forget the wine?
    Aged, I have resigned from office and returned.
    The wounded goose thinks of folding its wings,
    the old horse can no longer bear the bridle.
    No one passes through the forest hollows,
    dreams fly along paths of cloud.
    Without a cup to drink in such hours,
    how shall I endure this fading light?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The poem is structured as two stanzas, each beginning with the same question, reflecting the speaker''s repeated longing for wine in two different circumstances of hardship: military service on the frontier and retirement in old age.'
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of the wounded goose and old horse serves as metaphors for the speaker's own declining condition and weariness.
